I haven’t been posting much these days. I lost my father back in October, and I have been taking some time to work through it. I had been given the family task of scattering his ashes. I put a lot of thought into it, and I spend a lot of time in West Texas. Every time I go there when I come home I feel a big reset. All that big open space and quiet to think. It’s like it’s an opportunity to begin again. I decided the perfect spot was to scatter them atop of my favorite trail at Big Bend National Park. His 88th birthday would have been January 11th, so in honor of that this past Wednesday I set out and hiked, I sang, I wrote, I prayed, I gave thanks, and I took in the beautiful day. I found my way to the top of the trail. There I scattered his ashes, and I’d like to think the wind gave him the best possible views of that magical expanse. I am so grateful for this beautiful life I have with so many wonderful people in it. Dad thank you for all of it. Even the tough stuff. I know grief isn’t something that you just get over, but I think I let go of somethings up on that mountain that I really needed to. I’m back home now and feeling love and inspiration. I’m just trying to be as present as I can possibly be so I can make the most of this time I have here on this planet. I love you very much Dad. Rest in peace Arthur John Wennerstrom.

Last night was so special. I grew up in Dayton OH and @guidedbyvoicesofficial have had a huge influence on me over the years.  From song writing to the great live shows they put on. Bob Pollard is one of my heroes. It was such an honor to be a part of their 40th anniversary show in the hometown. And what a great bill! @builttospill is another big influence on me and I had heard they have been covering The Mountain lately, which absolutely blows my mind, so they joined us on stage to play the song together! We’ll get some video up soon. @wednesday_gurl rounded out the bill and they were incredible and sweet humans. I highly recommend you check them out. It was such a great evening and we were so happy to be a part of it.

Rolling into 2024 as wild and free as my hair on top of a Texas Mountain. 

I did the same exact hike to the day last year on my fathers birthday Jan 11th. Last year it was to scatter his ashes at the top of my favorite trail. This year I felt full of peace. It gave me the opportunity to reflect on this past year, where I’m at now and the personal growth. I like to say, you’re never exactly where you want to be because then you wouldn’t have anywhere to go. I have to stop and appreciate the growth. I feel tremendous gratitude for who I am and where I’ve come from. Even the adversity. Its all part of who I am. There’s no greater way to honor my parents and ancestors than to find the joy and peace in my life. Here’s to continuously learning how to walk through this life full of grace. May the coming year be filled with love, joy, and inspiration for each and everyone of you.
I write and sing tunes in the band @heartlessbastards. New album ‘A Beautiful Life’ is out now!
